GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 636
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/15/25
Short Title: Promoting Wholesome Content for Students. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
April 2, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT CONTENT THAT IS
3 HARMFUL TO MINORS IS NOT MADE AVAILABLE IN SCHOOLS AND TO
4 ESTABLISH A PRIVATE CAUSE OF ACTION FOR PARENTS, GUARDIANS, OR
5 RESIDENTS OF A COUNTY AGAINST A PUBLIC SCHOOL UNIT THAT IS
6 VIOLATING THOSE PROCEDURES.
7 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
8 SECTION 1. G.S. 115C-12 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
9 "(50) Database of Rejected Library Media. – The State Board shall maintain a
10 database of all library media rejected by public school units pursuant to Part
11 7 of Article 7B of this Chapter. The State Board shall update this database
12 annually and make the database publicly available on a website maintained by
13 the Department of Public Instruction."
14 SECTION 2.(a) Article 7B of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
15 adding a new Part to read:
16 "Part 7. Student Services.
17 "§ 115C-78. Library media.
18 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
19 (1) Approval. – Approval for library media to be added to a school library and
20 retained in a school library.
21 (2) Community library advisory committee. – A committee established by the
22 governing body of a public school unit pursuant to subsection (d) of this
23 section.
24 (3) Library media. – Any media, excluding textbooks, for independent use by
25 students and school personnel and not used as part of the standard course of
26 study for any grade or course, whether held in a formal school library or in a
27 classroom.
28 (4) Media. – Any electronic, print, or non-print resources, including pictures,
29 drawings, video recordings, films or other visual depictions or representations,
30 as well as written words.
31 (5) Parent. – A parent or legal guardian.
32 (6) Rejected. – Any library media that is reviewed by a public school unit and not
33 met with approval.
34 (7) School library. – Any location within a school that contains library media.
35 (8) Sexual activity. – As defined in G.S. 14-190.13.
*H636-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Governing bodies of public school units shall adopt a policy for the selection and
2 procurement of library media, including a recommendation review process. Approval of library
3 media shall be an ongoing process that includes the removal within one year of library media that
4 no longer meets the criteria for approval and the periodic replacement or repair of library media
5 still of educational value. This review shall include any library media that is donated to the public
6 school unit or a school within a public school unit.
7 (c) The policy adopted by the governing body of a public school unit pursuant to this
8 section shall meet the following requirements:
9 (1) The community library advisory committee shall identify library media to be
10 recommended for addition to a school library.
11 (2) The community library advisory committee shall review library media for
12 addition to a school library and determine whether the library media meets the
13 following criteria:
14 a. Supports and enriches students' personal learning and the standard
15 course of study for grades and courses offered at the school where the
16 library media would be available.
17 b. Meets high standards in literary, artistic, and aesthetic quality, as well
18 as technical aspects and physical format.
19 c. Is appropriate for the age, grade level, intellectual development, and
20 ability level of the students that will have access to the library media.
21 Library media that is appropriate for the age, grade level, intellectual
22 development, and ability level is library media that is suitable for
23 particular ages or age groups of children and adolescents based on
24 developing cognitive, emotional, and behavioral capacity typical for
25 the age or age group. Library media is not appropriate for the age,
26 grade level, intellectual development, and ability level for any age or
27 age group of children if it includes descriptions or visual depictions of
28 sexual activity or is pervasively vulgar.
29 d. Balances financial cost with need.
30 e. Complies with the Children's Internet Protection Act, 47 U.S.C. §
31 254(h)(5), including technology protection measures.
32 (3) The community library advisory committee shall submit recommendations to
33 the governing body of the public school unit for approval or denial.
34 (4) The governing body of the public school unit shall consider the recommended
35 library media at meetings of the body. While the library media is under review,
36 the governing body may request more information from the superintendent
37 about the library media or the author of the library media. Any member of the
38 governing body may make a motion to place recommended library media
39 before the body for approval. If no member makes a motion, then the library
40 media is not approved. Consideration of the recommended library media must
41 be completed within 60 days of the submission of the recommendation to the
42 governing body.
43 (5) When the community library advisory committee submits recommendations
44 to the governing body of the public school unit, all recommendations will be
45 placed on the public school unit's website and be accessible to the public. The
46 posting shall also include a form for submission of objections and instructions
47 for a parent, teacher, or resident of the county in which the public school unit
48 is located, to submit an objection to approval of the library media. The
49 submission must include information on how the library media fails to meet
50 the criteria for approval.
Page 2 House Bill 636-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) If any library media receives 10 or more letters of objection from parents,
2 teachers, or residents of the county in which the public school unit is located,
3 which state with specificity how the library media fails to meet the criteria for
4 approval, the superintendent shall submit those letters of objection to the
5 community library advisory committee. The committee shall review any
6 challenges received and make recommendations to the governing body
7 concerning the challenged library media. This subdivision applies to library
8 media recommended to the governing body of the public school unit for
9 approval and to library media that has been approved and included in a school
10 library.
11 (d) The governing body of each public school unit shall establish a community library
12 advisory committee composed of 10 members selected by the superintendent. The superintendent
13 shall select five parents of students enrolled in the public school unit and five employees of the
14 governing body of the public school unit. The community library advisory committee shall do
15 all of the following related to library media:
16 (1) Identify, evaluate, and recommend library media for approval by the
17 governing body of the public school unit.
18 (2) Investigate, evaluate, and make recommendations to the governing body of
19 the public school unit regarding objections to library media from parents,
20 teachers, and residents of the county in which the public school unit is located.
21 (e) The governing body of the public school unit shall publish on a website that is
22 accessible to the public and make available to a parent or resident of the county in which the
23 public school unit is located any library media that has been approved by the governing body and
24 the criteria established pursuant to this section used to select or procure the library media.
25 (f) Prior to any school in a public school unit conducting or partnering with a third party
26 to conduct a student book fair, the community library advisory committee shall conduct a review
27 of all media that will be made available to students at the book fair to determine if the media
28 meets the criteria listed in subdivision (2) of subsection (c) of this section. It shall be the express
29 duty of the community library advisory committee to ensure that no media be accepted by the
30 school or made available to students at the book fair that does not comply with this section.
31 (g) The governing body of the public school unit shall maintain a database of all rejected
32 library media and report on the contents of that database to the State Board of Education annually
33 by June 30.
34 "§ 115C-78.5. Remedies for violations of this Part.
35 (a) Civil Remedies. – In addition to any other remedies or procedures provided by law,
36 for any violation of this Part, a parent, legal guardian, or resident of the county in which the
37 public school unit is located may bring a cause of action against the public school unit for any of
38 the following forms of relief:
39 (1) Declaratory relief.
40 (2) Injunctive relief.
41 (3) Damages of five thousand dollars ($5,000) per violation.
42 (4) Reasonable attorneys' fees and costs.
43 (5) Any other appropriate relief as determined by the court.
44 (b) Exhaustion of Administrative Remedies. – Prior to filing a legal challenge pursuant
45 to subsection (a) of this section, a parent, guardian, or resident of the county shall exhaust all
46 administrative remedies available pursuant to this Chapter."
47 SECTION 2.(b) For library media which was purchased by a public school unit prior
48 to this act becoming law, the governing body of the public school unit shall use the community
49 library advisory committee to investigate and evaluate challenges. The process for consideration
50 shall be identical to the processes established in subdivision (c)(6) of G.S. 115C-78, as enacted
51 by this act.
